|<ref name="reuters-2021-01-12-mimecast">{{Cite web|title=Email security firm Mimecast says hackers hijacked its products to spy on customers|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-cyber-mimecast-idUSKBN29H22K|accessdate=2021-01-13|date=2021-01-12|work=U.S.|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112194050/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-global-cyber-mimecast-idUSKBN29H22K|archivedate=2021-01-12|quote=Three cybersecurity investigators, who spoke on condition of anonymity to discuss details of an ongoing probe, told Reuters they suspected the hackers who compromised Mimecast were the same group that broke into U.S. software maker SolarWinds and a host of sensitive U.S. government agencies.}}</ref><ref name="sw-2021-01-13-mimecast">{{Cite web|title=Mimecast Discloses Certificate Incident Possibly Related to SolarWinds Hack|url=https://www.securityweek.com/mimecast-discloses-certificate-incident-possibly-related-solarwinds-hack|accessdate=2021-01-13|date=2021-01-13|work=SecurityWeek.Com|quote= -{According to Mimecast, it learned from Microsoft that hackers had compromised a certificate used to authenticate Mimecast Continuity Monitor, Internal Email Protect (IEP), and Sync and Recover products with Microsoft 365 Exchange Web Services. ... The company has not shared any details about the attacks abusing the compromised certificate, but some experts have speculated that the certificate may have allowed the hackers to intercept Mimecast customers’ communications. ... According to Reuters, people with knowledge of the situation believe this incident may be related to the recently disclosed supply chain attack involving Texas-based IT management solutions provider SolarWinds.}- |archive-date=2021-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210317131954/https://www.securityweek.com/mimecast-discloses-certificate-incident-possibly-related-solarwinds-hack|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="tp-2021-01-12-mimecast">{{Cite web|title=Mimecast Certificate Hacked in Microsoft Email Supply-Chain Attack|url=https://threatpost.com/mimecast-certificate-microsoft-supply-chain-attack/162965/|accessdate=2021-01-13|author=Seals|date=2021-01-12|first=Tara|work=Threatpost|quote= -{Mimecast provides email security services that customers can apply to their Microsoft 365 accounts by establishing a connection to Mimecast’s servers... A compromise means that cyberattackers could take over the connection, though which inbound and outbound mail flows, researchers said. It would be possible to intercept that traffic, or possibly to infiltrate customers’ Microsoft 365 Exchange Web Services and steal information. 'The attack against Mimecast and their secure connection to Microsoft’s Office 365 infrastructure appears to be the work of the same sophisticated attackers that breached SolarWinds and multiple government agencies,' Saryu Nayyar, CEO at Gurucul, said via email.}- |archive-date=2021-03-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210317190704/https://threatpost.com/mimecast-certificate-microsoft-supply-chain-attack/162965/|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="sc-2021-01-13-mimecast">{{Cite web|title=SolarWinds attackers suspected in Microsoft authentication compromise|url=https://www.scmagazine.com/home/email-security/solarwinds-attackers-suspected-in-microsoft-authentication-compromise/|accessdate=2021-01-13|date=2021-01-12|work=SC Media|archive-date=2021-02-27|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227022128/https://www.scmagazine.com/home/email-security/solarwinds-attackers-suspected-in-microsoft-authentication-compromise/|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="tr-2021-01-12-mimecast">{{Cite web|title=Mimecast may also have been a victim of the SolarWinds hack campaign|url=https://www.techradar.com/news/mimecast-may-also-have-been-a-victim-of-the-solarwinds-hack-campaign|accessdate=2021-01-13|author=Spadafora|date=2021-01-12|first=Anthony|work=TechRadar|quote=The reason that Mimecast may have been attacked by the same threat actor behind the SolarWinds hack is due to the fact that these hackers often add authentication tokens and credentials to Microsoft Active Directory domain accounts in order to maintain persistence on a network and to achieve privilege escalation.|archive-date=2021-01-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210113104856/https://www.techradar.com/news/mimecast-may-also-have-been-a-victim-of-the-solarwinds-hack-campaign|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref name="wsj-2021-01-13-mimecast">{{Cite web|title=SolarWinds Hackers' Attack on Email Security Company Raises New Red Flags|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/solarwinds-hackers-attack-on-email-security-company-raises-new-red-flags-11610510375|accessdate=2021-01-13|author=McMillan|date=2021-01-13|first=Robert|work=WSJ|quote=The Mimecast hackers used tools and techniques that link them to the hackers who broke into Austin, Texas-based SolarWinds Corp., according to people familiar with the investigation. The link to the SolarWinds hackers was reported earlier by Reuters.|archive-date=2021-06-07|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210607055159/https://www.wsj.com/articles/solarwinds-hackers-attack-on-email-security-company-raises-new-red-flags-11610510375|dead-url=no}}</ref>
